When a lawyer presents a "recommendation," they are usually presenting the result of this equation without showing their work. Here is how we use this "Unwritten Law" as a defensive tool.

1. The Leverage Loss (A) vs. The Relationship Gain (B)
Lawyers operate in a "Small World." They will see that opposing counsel again next week in a different case. You, the client, are a "One-Time Player."
- The Peopleâ€™s Doctrine: If the lawyer suggests "playing nice" to build rapport (B), the litigant must demand to know which specific piece of discovery or motion (A) is being sacrificed to pay for that rapport.
1. The Billable/Efficiency Variable (C)
Litigation is exhausting for the firm. If a case becomes too complex or the "math" of the contingency fee or retainer starts to look thin, the lawyer will subconsciously (or consciously) look for an "Exit Ramp."
- The Peopleâ€™s Doctrine: We treat C as the "Burn Rate." When C gets too high, the lawyerâ€™s advice will naturally skew toward "Dettlement" or "Simplification," even if it hurts your probability of success (D).
1. The Outcome Probability (D)
This is the only variable the client actually cares about.
- The Peopleâ€™s Doctrine: To protect D, the litigant must use Evidence-Based Law. If the lawyer cannot point to a specific rule or piece of evidence that justifies a retreat, they are likely optimizing for A, B, or C.
